  "texts": [
    "The average degree measures the mean number of edges per node.",
    "For the causal map in Fig. 1, this would result in an average degree of 2+3+2+3 4 = 2.5; note that it is not equivalent to simply summing up the number of edges and dividing by the number of nodes (5/4 = 1.25).",
    "The density measures the number of existing edges in the map as a ratio of the maximum number of edges that the map could have if every node was linked to every other node.",
    "Given the same example, the density would be 5 4×3 = 0.416.",
    "Unlike mind maps which are rooted trees and hence forbid cycles, causal maps frequently contain cycles."
  ],
